import java.io.*; // Import necessary classes needed at the top of our file – File, IOException etc.   -> 'IOException' in case a problem arises during reading files to disk: e.g., unable access directory due permissions issues and so on ... thus avoiding NullPointerExceptions which are very hard for beginners or even experienced developers with their tools
import java.util.*; // Import necessary classes needed at the top of our file – List, ArrayList etc.. -> 'List', you can use Collection Framework interfaces as well (like Iterable in case we have a list) and its methods like add(), remove()... thus avoiding NullPointerExceptions which are very hard for beginners or experienced developers
import java.nio.*; // Import necessary classes needed at the top of our file – Path, Files etc.. -> 'Files' is more powerful as it can interact with directories/file systems (like creating new files and directory), so when used to read a local disk folder everything inside will be available ... thus avoiding NullPointerExceptions which are very hard for beginners or experienced developers
